<script src="http://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js" type="text/javascript">
</script></div>
<p>The Motorola Admiral will be available to some Sprint customers online for ordering as early as Oct. 23rd. The smartphone will feature the new Direct Connect feature from Sprint. The new addition will offer its user an Android powered push-to-talk capability.</p>
<p>The Admiral from Motorola and using the Sprint network, will be powered by a 1GHz CPU and will run on the Android 2.3 OS or Gingerbread. The smartphone will have a 3.1-inch touchscreen display. The mobile device will have a QWERTY keyboard from which the user will be able to use the various programs.</p>
<p>The Admiral will be able to show off its toughness by the fact that it has been built according to Military Standard 810G. The smartphone will be able to withstand most things that happen during everyday use. The Gorilla Glass touchscreen display adds to the mobile devices sturdiness by being scratch resistant.</p>
<p>Being that the Admiral is an Android device, it will be able to use the mobile resources of Google. The mobile device will also include such software as Quickoffice and Adobe Flash Player. A 5MP camera with autofocus and autoflash will round out the standard features the smartphone users have come to expect.</p>
<p>The smartphone will have the ability to connect to Sprint&#8217;s 3G network, Wi-Fi, or Bluetooth. The smartphone may cost under $100 (with 2 year agreement and $50 mail-rebate and reward card)  and will be available in Sprint stores around Nov. 23rd. Any of these features may change prior to the actual launch. <a rel="nofollow" href="http://redirectingat.com?id=10040X685899&xs=1&url=http%3A%2F%2Fnewsroom.sprint.com%2Farticle_display.cfm%3Farticle_id%3D2078&sref=rss">Click here</a> for more details.</p>
